<TITLE> Tigers lose 3 wickets before early tea </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Chittagong, Jan 18 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh let slip a good start to their first innings before bad light forced an early tea on the second day of the first Test against India at the Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium in Chittagong on Monday. Openers Tamim Iqbal and Imrul Kayes put on 53 runs before the latter was out lbw for 23 to Zaheer Khan. First former ICL rebel Shahriar Nafees' return to the five-day game lasted only three balls before he was caught in the slips off Ishant Sharma. Just before the players came off the ground Tamim Iqbal, who was playing fluently on 31 off 45 balls with six fours was clean bowled by Zaheer. Bangladesh had negotiated the last 20 minutes before the lunch interval taking their score to 21 without loss after dismissing the tourists for 243. India, resuming the second morning on 213-8, owed their final total to Sachin Tendulkar who carried his bat to remain 105 not out off 166 balls with 11 fours and two sixes. It was the batting maestro's 44th Test century, and 89th in internationals. It was also his fourth hundred against Bangladesh. Tendulkar scored 29 of the 30 runs India managed manoeuvring the strike well and adding some respectability to the tourists' total. Both Bangladesh captain Shakib Al Hasan and Shahadat Hossain reached five-fors - it was Shakib's sixth in 15 Tests and Shahadat's third. Shakib finished with 5-62 while Shahadat 
